        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4202973403" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7501950342201299542">(1 star for this particular edition which is so badly formatted with the pages from the physical book scanned into the text in between the kindle text which is very distracting) <br/><br/>Beautifully written and moving stories of lives in Palestine particularly the novella Men in the Sun which follows three men post the 1948 catastrophe as they attempt to reach Kuwait for jobs where they can earn money for a better life. The other stories are about being forced from the land and becoming refugees in The L</span>
  <span id="freeText7501950342201299542" style="display:none">(1 star for this particular edition which is so badly formatted with the pages from the physical book scanned into the text in between the kindle text which is very distracting) <br /><br />Beautifully written and moving stories of lives in Palestine particularly the novella Men in the Sun which follows three men post the 1948 catastrophe as they attempt to reach Kuwait for jobs where they can earn money for a better life. The other stories are about being forced from the land and becoming refugees in The Land of Oranges, 'If You Were a Horse' deals in myth and folklore as does A Hand in the Grave' and The Falcon, while Umm Saad looks at life in the refugee camps and a mother's love and fear for her son. Finally Letter from Gaza illustrates a man's love for his country and responsibility towards it and to those who are also fighting for something more. <br /><br />Those are short descriptions that don't do justice to the emotion of these stories, to the heart break of the characters nor of the beauty of the writing. Ghassan Khafani was tragically killed as a young man and not only does this make you wonder what else he could have written but how he would have viewed what has happened to the Palestinian people since the 1960's. Always an essential read but more so in the light of the events of 2021.<br /><br /><br /><b>'In the last ten years you have done nothing but wait. You have needed ten big hungry years to be convinced that you have lost your trees, your house, your youth, and your whole village.'<br /><br />'I was sure that the God we had known in Palestine had left it too, and was a refugee in some place that I did not know, unable to find a solution to his own problems.'<br /><br />'I loved Nadia from habit, the same habit that made me love all that generation which has been so brought up on defeat and displacement that it had come to think that a happy life was a kind of social deviation.'</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="7501950342201299542" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


