    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3065915968" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3065915968" />
    <a title="Aisha (thatothernigeriangirl)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38116779-aisha-thatothernigeriangirl"><img alt="Aisha (thatothernigeriangirl)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595210664p2/38116779.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3065915968?book_show_action=true">Apr 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aisha (thatothernigeriangirl)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aisha (thatothernigeriangirl)" href="/user/show/38116779-aisha-thatothernigeriangirl">Aisha (thatothernigeriangirl)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780894108570" href="/book/show/125251.Men_in_the_Sun_and_Other_Palestinian_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3065915968" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5291070123198734554"><br/>It is a collection of 7 stories, and I found the titular story to be most impactful. It left me with an immense sadness for the characters upon completion; and more importantly, I really enjoyed Kanafani’s writing style.<br/><br/>Maybe because Arabic is a language that can be poetic — or maybe that was just his style— many of the stories, especially the titular one, had parts that read more like poetry than prose. They weren’t poetic prose; just outrightly poetic.<br/><br/>Also pertinent is the apparent absence of </span>
  <span id="freeText5291070123198734554" style="display:none"><br />It is a collection of 7 stories, and I found the titular story to be most impactful. It left me with an immense sadness for the characters upon completion; and more importantly, I really enjoyed Kanafani’s writing style.<br /><br />Maybe because Arabic is a language that can be poetic — or maybe that was just his style— many of the stories, especially the titular one, had parts that read more like poetry than prose. They weren’t poetic prose; just outrightly poetic.<br /><br />Also pertinent is the apparent absence of anything obviously political in the stories. It is as if Kanafani wanted to show readers the raw implications of the Palestinian displacement without leaving room for us to diminish these suffering with our political jargons. Like he was saying: “look! these are the struggles that Palestinians face as a result of the occupation. And we both know who the perpetrator is but don’t focus on that; focus on our stories; the rawness of our emotions”<br /><br />His decision to tell Palestinian stories in this way doesn’t of course diminish the work of other authors who chose to highlight both the stories and the roles of the Israel forces; this style is just another valid form of amplifying Palestinian stories.<br /><br />I gave the collection a 3.5 stars because some of the other stories that followed the titular stories were underwhelming, but nonetheless, I highly recommend checking Ghassan Kanafani’s works. I’ll be reading his other translated book soon</span>
  <a data-text-id="5291070123198734554" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

